data.content:
Now I have the full picture. Here's the answer:

## What happened

C# 14 introduces new **built-in span conversions**. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, overload resolution now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

This works fine in regular code, but **expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` method calls**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by preventing the implicit span conversion. Any of these work:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the compiler from choosing the `MemoryExtensions` span overload, keeping the expression tree representable.
